To eliminate arrays in JavaScript that contain identical digit combinations, regardless of their arrangement, you can utilize the Set data structure along with sorting. This method ensures that the comparison between arrays is based on their unique digit combinations. Here's how you can achieve this:

```javascript
function removeDuplicates(arrays) {
    const seen = new Set();
    return arrays.filter(array => {
        const sortedArray = array.sort((a, b) => a - b).join('');
        if (seen.has(sortedArray)) {
            return false;
        }
        seen.add(sortedArray);
        return true;
    });
}
```

This function works by iterating over each array in the input collection. For each array, it sorts its elements in ascending order, converts the sorted array into a string, and checks if this string has been encountered before using the Set `seen`. If it has, the current array is considered a duplicate and is not included in the output; otherwise, it is added to the set and included in the result.

When you call `removeDuplicates` with an array of arrays as its argument, it returns a new array containing only the arrays with unique digit combinations.

For example, given the following input:

