When it comes to querying data through an interface rather than its implementation using Java Persistence API (JPA), we can leverage the concept of interfaces as target classes in our queries.


We define an interface that represents the structure of the data we want to retrieve, without any specific implementation details.


In our JPA repository or DAO class, we then specify the interface as the target class for our query, allowing us to execute the query against the interface and receive the results as instances of the implementing class.


This decouples our query logic from the specific implementation of the entity class, making our code more flexible and maintainable.


By using an interface as the target class in our JPA query, we can take advantage of polymorphism and achieve a higher level of abstraction in our code.


To illustrate this, let's consider an example where we have two entity classes `Employee` and `Manager`, both implementing a common interface `Person`. We can define a JPA query that targets the `Person` interface, allowing us to retrieve all employees or managers without having to know the specifics of their implementations.


```java
public interface Person {
    // Common attributes and methods for Employee and Manager
}

@Entity
public class Employee implements Person {
    // Specific attributes and methods for Employee
}

@Entity
public class Manager implements Person {
    // Specific attributes and methods for Manager
}

public class PersonRepository {
    @PersistenceContext
    private EntityManager em;

    public List<Person> findPersons() {
        return em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Person p", Person.class).getResultList();
    }
}
```

