To configure a JavaScript function for scrolling without surpassing the lower boundary of its parent element, you'll want to calculate the maximum scrollable area based on the parent's dimensions and the child's offset position within that parent. This involves using the `offsetTop` and `offsetLeft` properties to determine the child's current position relative to its parent, as well as the `clientHeight` and `scrollHeight` properties to get the parent's height and total content height respectively. You can then adjust your `.scrollTop()` and `.scrollLeft()` values accordingly to prevent scrolling beyond the visible boundaries. Here's a simplified example of how you might implement this logic:



```javascript
function scrollFunc(element, bool) {
  // Get the parent element's dimensions
  var parent = element.parentNode;

  // Calculate the maximum scrollable area
  var maxHeight = parent.clientHeight;
  var maxScrollY = parent.scrollHeight - maxHeight;

  // Adjust the scroll position if necessary
  if (bool) {
    // Scroll to top
    element.scrollTop = Math.min(element.scrollTop, 0);
  } else {
    // Scroll to bottom
    element.scrollTop = Math.max(0, element.scrollHeight - maxHeight);

    // Prevent scrolling past parent's boundaries
    if (element.scrollTop > maxScrollY) {
      element.scrollTop = maxScrollY;
    }
  }
}
